Analysis This question tests the basic knowledge of probability and the concept of mathematical expectation, as well as the ability to apply probability knowledge to solve practical problems.
Solution (1) Without taking preventive measures, the total cost, which is the expected loss, is $400 \times 0.3=120$ (ten thousand yuan);
(2) If only measure A is taken, the cost of preventive measures is 45 ten thousand yuan, and the probability of a sudden event occurring is $1-0.9=0.1$, the expected loss is $400 \times 0.1=40$ (ten thousand yuan), so the total cost is $45+40=85$ (ten thousand yuan);
(3) If only preventive measure B is taken, the cost of preventive measures is 30 ten thousand yuan, and the probability of a sudden event occurring is $1-0.85=0.15$, the expected loss is $400 \times 0.15=60$ (ten thousand yuan), so the total cost is $30+60=90$ (ten thousand yuan);
(4) If both preventive measures A and B are taken, the cost of preventive measures is $45+30=75$ (ten thousand yuan), and the probability of a sudden event occurring is $(1-0.9)(1-0.85)=0.015$, the expected loss is $400 \times 0.015=6$ (ten thousand yuan), so the total cost is $75+6=81$ (ten thousand yuan).

In summary, comparing the total costs in (1), (2), (3), and (4), it is clear that both preventive measures A and B should be taken to minimize the total cost.
!Comment This question mainly tests the concept of mathematical expectation and knowledge related to independent events.

